 </disp-formula>where the notation is analogous to that in Eq. (
 <xref rid="Equ1" ref-type="" class="xref">1</xref>) except that now 
 <italic class="italic">N</italic> unique distributions are estimated corresponding to each virtual observation. Virtual observation Δ
 <italic class="italic">V</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">t</italic>−1,
  <italic class="italic">i</italic>
 </sub> is treated as a sample from an underlying normal distribution; 
 <italic class="italic">μ</italic>(Δ
 <italic class="italic">V</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">t</italic>−1
  <italic class="italic">,i</italic>
 </sub>) and 
 <italic class="italic">υ</italic>(Δ
 <italic class="italic">V</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">t−</italic>1,
  <italic class="italic">i</italic>
 </sub>) are the underlying change in mean temperature in the current (
 <italic class="italic">t−</italic>1) and future (
 <italic class="italic">t</italic>) time periods, respectively, given each virtual observation Δ
 <italic class="italic">V</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">t−</italic>1,
